Information
This documents how to setup a repository and get it working on your local machine as Delegate does with coding rules and generated code.

Create a new empty repository in Azure DevOps
Clone the new repository on your local machine and open file explorer on the path where your repository has been cloned to.
Open another explorer and navigate to an existing repository fx. kl-iot-provider-cpms-monta-api
Copy the files "atc-coding-rules-updater.json" and "atc-coding-rules-updater.ps1" from the existing repository into the new one.

Open both files in VS Code
The "atc-coding-rules-updater.ps1" should look like this
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Clear-Host
Write-Host "Update atc-coding-rules"
dotnet tool update -g atc-coding-rules-updater

$currentPath = Get-Location

atc-coding-rules-updater run `
  -p $currentPath `
  --optionsPath $currentPath'\atc-coding-rules-updater.json' `
  --verbose
--------------------------------------------------------------------
and the "atc-coding-rules-updater.json" should look like this
--------------------------------------------------------------------
{
  "projectTarget": "DotNet10",
  "mappings": {
    "sample": { "paths": [ "sample" ] },
    "src": { "paths": [ "src" ] },
    "test": { "paths": [ "test" ] }
  }
}
---------------------------------------------------------------------
If it includes other mappings than src and test, you must delete them (it not applicable in this solution)
Run the "atc-coding-rules-updater.ps1" in the terminal as administrator in the correct path where the .ps1 is located.

Else you will be prompted with an organization name (enter KL) and a repository name (enter a name for your solution, which aligns with that of the other repositories)
image.png
Your repository should after a successful run of the .ps1 contain (opened in VS code):
.vs
src
test
.editorconfig
atc-coding-rules-updater.ps1
atc-coding-rules-updater.json
Directory.Build.props
README.md (if added)

The Organization name and the Repository name given in the terminal can be found and edited in the "Directory.Build.props" file
Create a new solution in the "src" folder in the repository via Visual studio

In case of a web api
Use an existing repository to add the folder called "src/ScriptAndSpecifications" in the src folder as well. Remove all other files than these below and rename them to match your reposistory/api.
NAME.spec.api.v1.yaml
generate-NAME-context.ps1

Open these files in VS code and edit the sections where your project name differs from the existing fx. in the .yaml file rewrite info.title, info.description, tags.name . Paths/Models etc. should be cleaned out, since those should be re-done for a new API (A helpful tool to edit in paths/model section is called Stoplight.io ).

Run the generate.ps1 located in the ScriptAndSpecification folder using a terminal
Go to Visual studio, right click on src, add existing project and choose the .csproj file

Repeat for alle existing projects you want located in src (generated by the atc-rest-api-generator)
Create a test project for every project and reference the correct libraries/projects.
